description.plain:
Navraj Singh Goraya (born November 3, 1989), popularly known as NAV, is an Indian-Canadian recording artist, record producer, and engineer from Rexdale, Ontario, Canada, a district of Toronto. His parents are both from the state of Punjab in India and are fluent in the Punjabi language; NAV himself is fluent in both English and Punjabi and practices the religion of Sikhism, the religion the majority of Punjabs practice.

Following in the footsteps of Canadian singer The Weeknd, the co-founder and leader of XO and a frequent collaborator of his, NAV has preferred to let his SoundCloud do the talking in the early stages of his career. Although going largely unnoticed at the time of its release, NAV’s first noteworthy production credit was in July 2015 when he helped co-produce Drake’s diss track towards Meek Mill, “Back to Back.”

After hearing a string of successful SoundCloud hits, including the self-produced “Myself,” in 2016, Amir “Cash” Esmailian, the co-founder and manager of XO, reached out to NAV, giving him an opportunity to expand from the revolutionary music platform. NAV has grabbed numerous features since linking up with The Weeknd and the rest of XO, consisting of Belly, 88GLAM, and Black Atlass. His first and arguably most recognizable feature (which he also solely produced) is Travis Scott’s September 2016 song, “beibs in the trap,” from Travis' sophomore studio album, Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight.

He released “Some Way,” featuring The Weeknd–NAV’s first song to feature another artist–on February 15, 2017. The song is the lead single of his debut self-titled mixtape. Nine days later, February 24, 2017, NAV released the mixtape, featuring the hits “Some Way” and “Myself.” NAV solely produced many songs off the album, and has production credits on every single song. Following the mixtape, he and Atlanta producer, Metro Boomin,, released a collaborative mixtape, titled Perfect Timing, on July 21, 2017.

On May 18, 2018, NAV released his debut studio album, RECKLESS, which featured the hits “Wanted You,” featuring Lil Uzi Vert, “Freshman List,” and “Champion,” featuring Travis Scott. Following the album, NAV was featured alongside Gunna, a frequent collaborator of both NAV and Travis, on Travis' August 2018 song, “YOSEMITE,” from his third studio album, ASTROWORLD. Then, on October 16, 2018, NAV released a collaborative mixtape with Guap Tarantino entirely produced by ATL Jacob titled 1 Night.

Following Lil Uzi Vert’s retirement claims, NAV made similar claims. However, on March 14, 2019, NAV’s manager Cash dropped NAV’s unofficial EP, Brown Boy, which consisted of five unreleased songs from Cash’s phone. Just two days after the release, NAV announced that his sophomore studio album would be titled Bad Habits and would be released on March 22, 2019, featuring the hits “Know Me” and “Tap,” featuring Meek Mill, as well as the album being executive produced by himself, Cash and The Weeknd. NAV released a deluxe version of the album four days later, on March 26, 2019, including all the songs from Brown Boy plus three new songs. During the week ending March 28, 2019, Bad Habits debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200 with 82,000 equivalent album units moved. This marks NAV’s first album to hit the top spot.

On May 8, 2020, NAV released his third studio album, Good Intentions, featuring his highest-charting hit “Turks,” with Gunna featuring Travis Scott (the same artists who collaborated on “YOSEMITE”), as well as executive produced by himself, Cash, and The Weeknd again. NAV released a deluxe version of the album three days later, on May 11, 2020, with the second half being his mixtape, Brown Boy 2, a sequel to his March 2019 mixtape, which became his second #1 album on the Billboard 200.

songs.title: Myself

description.plain:
“Myself” is the opening track to NAV’s self-titled debut mixtape and first project. He explores the world of depression and self-consciousness, stating that he feels more like himself when he’s under the influence of drugs like lean, marijuana, and MDMA.

NAV released the song to his SoundCloud account on January 12, 2016. It appeared on his unofficial September 2016 mixtape, The Introduction. A little more than a year later, it found an official release as part of his eponymous project on February 24, 2017.

The official music video for the song was released on March 22, 2017.

description.plain:
“Some Way” is NAV’s lead single from his upcoming self-titled mixtape, dropping on Feb 24th. Both artists throw subliminal jabs at Justin Bieber, who mocked The Weeknd’s single “Starboy,” calling Abel’s music “wack” during an Instagram live stream at the 2017 Grammy awards. The most obvious diss comes at the end of The Weeknd’s verse:

I think your girl, think your girl, fell in love with me / She say my fuck, and my tongue game a remedy

“Some Way” is the first collaboration between NAV and the XO founder, The Weeknd.

songs.full_title: Wanted You by NAV (Ft. Lil Uzi Vert)
songs.title: Wanted You

description.plain:
On “Wanted You,” NAV teams up with Lil Uzi Vert for a melodic, catchy song all about girls, money, and relationships ruined by cheating. It is featured on NAV’s debut studio album, RECKLESS (2018), and was released on November 3, 2017, coinciding with NAV’s 28th birthday.

NAV and Uzi have collaborated two times on NAV and Metro Boomin’s collaborative mixtape, Perfect Timing, on the tracks, “NAVUZIMETRO#PT2” and “A$AP Ferg”.

The song’s cover art was posted out-of-the-blue in a now-deleted post on NAV’s Instagram on November 1, 2017, two days before the song’s release, foreshadowing the date of release along with the cover art. He captioned it:

Wanted you ft. my brother @liluzivert out this Friday Nov 3rd my b-day! 🎂🎂🎂 from my new album coming soon!

On December 8, 2017, a short music video from the NAV’s full verse to the second half of the Uzi’s full verse was released. On January 12, 2018, an animated video of the full song was released.

songs.title: Up

description.plain: On “Up,” NAV goes in-depth about his rise to stardom, coming from nothing to now being wealthy and famous. In addition to this, he talks about the drawbacks of fame and fortune, stating how people can love you when you’re down & hate you when you’re successful. Furthermore, NAV makes it clear he’s a drug user, referencing recreational drugs such as Percocet, lean and MDMA.

songs.title: Champion

description.plain:
On “Champion,“ NAV reunites with frequent collaborator Travis Scott for an energetic banger. On the track, the two artists rap about their various successes and conquests, likening themselves to NBA champions.

The two also drop numerous pop-culture references to The Matrix, Future, and possibly even Rihanna and Kendall Jenner.

The track is featured on NAV’s debut studio album, RECKLESS, which was released on May 18, 2018.

An official music video was released on August 9, 2018, featuring many collaborators of Travis' album ASTROWORLD, consisting of NAV, Travis, Gunna, Sheck Wes, Don Toliver.

“Tap” serves as the first collaboration between NAV and Meek Mill. The track is featured on NAV’s sophomore studio album, Bad Habits. On the track, the rappers discuss their privileged lives and discuss their humble origins.

NAV released the official music video for the track three months after its release, on June 13, 2019.

songs.title: Fell in Love

description.plain:
“Fell in Love” explores the extent of NAV’s extravagant lifestyle, filled with drama, drug use, sex, money, and fame. This is a continuing theme in NAV’s music as he wants to show off how far he’s come since being from a working-class background in Rexdale, Toronto, to living in LA. His hit single, “Myself,” is an example of this:

I remember being a kid my teachers told me I wouldn’t be shit
Diamonds in my pinky, look like water, make me seasick

songs.title: TTD

description.plain:
Ten Toes Down is one of the songs NAV released before his most recent album NAV, this is third oldest from SoundCloud, behind “The Man” and “Take Me Simple”. Since he found a spot for it at the end of his album, the song most definitely meant something for him.

“Ten Toes Down” (also known as TTD) could refer to NAV saying he needs to stay on his toes, aware of friends, and other rappers who might catch him on his heels.
You don’t want to get caught on your heels, meaning unaware and unprepared when things go wrong. Staying on all ten of his toes is vital for NAV, otherwise he can be easily knocked off from where he is, physically and in the rap game.

songs.title: Freshman List

description.plain:
Following on the heels of “Wanted You” Nav returns with a new single, “Freshman List,” produced by Charlie Handsome and past collaborator Rex Kudo. The track is likely from Nav´s upcoming third project. In an interview with Tim Westwood in March 2018 Nav stated that the album is mostly completed and will be substantially different from his previous releases, in part because he will handle some production.

The tracks title is both a reference to his upcoming Freshman Tour but also to the annual XXL Freshman list. On the track, Nav explains that he isn’t on 2018’s list despite having gained mainstream success and important co-signs from the likes of Rolling Stone and The Weeknd. After dropping the track, Nav unleashed some stinging criticism of the list,calling out XXL on Twitter and Instagram, explaining that he did not want to play any of his new music or pander to the magazine.

Following the release of the song, some of Nav’s contemporaries, like Quavo tweeted out their support.

songs.title: Good for It

description.plain:
NAV explores his newfound fame and money and outlines what he is able to do now. He used to be broke in the Rex but now that he’s with XO and has power, money, drugs, women, and fame are just another luxury.

The official music video was released to NAV’s YouTube channel on April 12th, 2017. It features footage from his concert at The Mod Club in Toronto on April 6th, some clips from The Weeknd’s Starboy: Legend of the Fall Tour concerts in London on March 7th and 8th, as well as some video footage from what seems to be a few different afterparties

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yqo_uNbRkJ0&feature=youtu.be

songs.title: Glow Up

description.plain:
On “Glow Up,” NAV raps about his growth into success and fame, and the luxuries he now enjoys with it – fitting for the title of the song, as a glow up is defined as “going from the bottom to the top to the point of disbelief.”

“Glow Up” was leaked on May 17, 2018 along with the rest of the album, a day before its official release.

description.plain: NAV reunites with Lil Baby on “Don’t Need Friends,” a standout track from Emergency Tsunami. The two rap about their success and how their haters have no affect on their successes, whilst also touching up on their usual lavish lifestyles. The official music video was released three days after the track’s release on November 9, 2020.

songs.title: Run It Up

description.plain:
“Run It Up” is a braggadocios track from NAV and Pop Smoke, on which both rappers discuss the increase their wealth and status has seen with their rise to fame.

The song is one of two Pop features released on May 8, 2020, along with Lil Tjay’s “Zoo York.” Both tracks are the late rapper’s first posthumous musical appearances since his untimely passing on February 19, 2020.

A demo of the track was leaked on February 8, 2020, under the name “Cap Cap Cap” with an open verse. An updated version was played on Cash’s live along with “Top Dog.”

songs.title: Tussin

description.plain:
“Tussin” is a song where NAV and Young Thug describe their recreational use of the cough syrup, Tussionex. Tussionex contains Hydrocodone, a highly addictive substance that makes the medicine more appealing to users and can ultimately lead to abuse.

Tussionex is a extended release Hydrocodone/ chlorpheniramine cough syrup which is much more potent than the typical promethazine/codeine syrup which is used to mix “lean”.

The outro gained attention due to the lyrics about Thug being attracted to his dope dealing auntie.

songs.title: Habits

description.plain:
“Habits” is the long-awaited track from Toronto rapper NAV. Initially, “Habits” was supposed to be released with a Lil Uzi Vert feature on the original version.

NAV made an announcement via Instagram upon the night of March 21, 2019, that due to DJ Drama and DJ Don Cannon, Lil Uzi Vert is unable to have his verse approved in time for NAV’s album. NAV reportedly paid $100,000 for the Lil Uzi Vert feature. Hence, “(NO UZI)”.

NAV eventually released a solo “Habits” along with the deluxe version of his fourth studio album: Bad Habits.

songs.title: Know Me

description.plain:
“Know Me” is a boastful banger by Canadian rapper NAV. The song illustrates another example of him displaying the desirable repercussions of having wealth and fame in the music industry. Throughout the song, he drops references to expensive clothing and jewelry, while also rapping about the drugs he takes.

This was released on November 2, 2018, a day before NAV’s 29th birthday. It serves as the lead single of his sophomore studio album, Bad Habits, which was released in March 2019 and debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200. The song had been teased on numerous occasions throughout the year before its eventual release. The song’s official music video was released on November 8, 2018, six days after its release.

description.plain:
On “Sleep,” NAV flexes his ability to gain female attention and get them to sleep with him. Before his rise to stardom, he has always struggled with attracting women, so there’s so no surprise majority of his tracks talk about women in a objectifying way. For example, on “Up”, NAV implies sleeping with women is not a problem anymore:

Remember these bitches ain’t wanna fuck
Now she give me head outside of Toys R Us

This is the 4th track he has produced himself without the help of others on his self-titled mixtape, NAV.

songs.title: Saint Laurenttt

description.plain:
On “Saint Laurenttt,“ NAV raps a slow track on how he’ll do anything for his girl, including buy her Saint Laurent and other designer fashion brands.

Yves Saint Laurent, or just Saint Laurent, is a French fashion company founded in 1961. They specialize in handbags, clothing, and other accessories.

NAV’s expressed his love for the brand countless times before, including on his March 2019 track “Go To Hell,“ on which he raps:

You can tell I’m gettin' money by what I got on
Supreme, Gucci, Louis, Fendi, and some Saint Laurent

songs.title: EAT

description.plain:
The tenth track off RECKLESS, “Eat” marks the second collaboration between NAV and Atlanta rapper Gunna, the first being Gunna’s 2018 track “Car Sick.” “Eat” sees the duo going back and forth, detailing their lavish lifestyles, designer clothes and trap life, among other topics.

The track is produced by Turbo who has produced many songs for Gunna.

songs.title: Never Change

description.plain:
After the introduction track, NAV reveals the reality of his lifestyle and how he abuses it for a good time. The then-28-year-old XO artist acknowledges his old age while mentioning his fear of losing the “rockstar” way of life.

Lil Uzi Vert, a close companion of NAV who has featured on this and previous projects, believes that “If you’re over the age of 25, you’re an OLD N***A.”

songs.title: Just Happened

description.plain: In the 7th track from RECKLESS, NAV reminisces about an old love with whom his relationship has gone sour. Although he admits to “thinking with his dick” in the second verse, he tries to assure this girl that he is still the same guy he always was and that he is sorry for breaking her heart. He wants her to forgive him and be able to share in his newfound success.

songs.title: Brown Boy

description.plain:
“Brown Boy“ is from the perspective of NAV’s haters. The track touches on how he’s perceived as a “brown boy” (referring to his Indian heritage) in the rap game.

NAV rapped from a similar perspective in his 2017 track “Did You See NAV?“ – in which he similarly details his life from the third person:

Did you see NAV? He was off the Perkys, he was leaning
Don’t try to take his chain, he’s surrounded by them demons
He had a bunch of bad bitches lining up to meet him
They reselling the tickets a thousand dollars just to see him

songs.title: To My Grave

description.plain:
On “To My Grave,” NAV opens us about his frustration with loyalty, boasts about his materialistic items, lavish lifestyle, and gang activity which set the tone for the rest of the album.

Featuring a distorted brass melody mixed in with piercing keys which OZ and Pro Logic produced, pacey, yet basic trap drums drive the energy of the track as NAV floats effortlessly on the hook, delivering you a glimpse of exactly what he is all about.

songs.title: Go to Hell

description.plain: “Go To Hell” is the introductory track to NAV’s 2019 unofficial EP, Brown Boy. It was then later added on the deluxe version of NAV’s second studio album, Bad Habits as the twentieth track. The song heavily focuses on the success of his career in music and hardships he’s had to face throughout his life.

songs.title: Vetement Socks

Produced by powerhouse duo Wheezy & Turbo, alongside Bak and Frankie Bash, this track undeniably stands out due to NAV’s clever flows and lyrics, without forgetting to mention his unique way of flexing.

songs.title: Tension

description.plain: “Tension” is the fifth track on NAV’s second studio album, Bad Habits. As the title states, NAV feels a lot of tension since gaining more recognition in the music industry. Alternatively, this tension is also a positive as he is finally gaining the appreciation for his work as a producer and a rapper.

songs.full_title: Habits (Original) by NAV (Ft. Lil Uzi Vert)
songs.title: Habits (Original)

description.plain:
“Habits” is a long-awaited track by NAV, first previewed almost two years ago before the release of Pefect Timing. Towards the release of the Bad Habits, NAV announced that Lil Uzi Vert was also featured on the song.

NAV publicly stated that the song wouldn’t make the album as Uzi couldn’t get his verse cleared by his label, even going as far as to scratch the title out of the tracklist. Prior to this in a now-expired Instagram story, NAV had “deleted” the song from his computer in another ploy to tease fans.

“Habits” was eventually released on the deluxe version of Bad Habits, although it did not include Lil Uzi Vert’s verse. A censored version of the track leaked on April 9, 2019, and was later played on The Weeknd’s Beats1 Radio: MEMENTO MORI on April 27.

Aside from the title, the song explores NAV’s come up story, having exorbitant amounts of money, and spending it on jewelry and designer clothing like it’s nothing.

songs.full_title: Hold Your Breath by NAV (Ft. Gunna)
songs.title: Hold Your Breath

description.plain:
On “Hold Your Breath,” the tenth track of NAV’s sophomore studio album, Bad Habits, he reunites with his close friend and frequent collaborator Gunna. The two team up to rap about their expensive jewelry, which is called “drip” in slang. They boast about their expensive lifestyles and taunt those who do not live the same lifestyle that they do, while also discussing  and making references to their drug usage, sexual endeavors, and weaponry style.

NAV often raps about the things discussed in the songs. He has rapped very similar lines on other tracks on Bad Habits, such as “Tap,” “Price on My Head,” “Tussin,” and “Time Piece.” All these songs share a common line about diamonds, comparing it to either something.

Gunna himself is considered to be the founder of drip. At the time of this track’s release, the word “drip” was the starting word of every project in his discography: his Drip Season trilogy, his collaborative mixtape Drip Harder with Lil Baby, and his mixtape Drip or Drown and his debut studio album, which is its sequel.

songs.title: Did You Wrong

description.plain:
On “Did You Wrong,“ NAV explains his regrets with the mistakes he made with a good girl. He’s had his fair share of women (and still has his choices), but as soon as he found the girl of his dreams, he messed it up.

The track was originally teased with a snippet on NAV’s XO Records manager Cash’s Instagram on October 15, 2019.

songs.title: Stuck with Me

description.plain: In “Stuck with Me,” NAV discusses his difficulties finding a woman he feels is worth keeping by him, but also his own struggles showing true love. He can give a girl all the presents in the world and supply her with the means to live a lavish lifestyle, but she’s still only “stuck with him;” she’s not there because she loves him, or because she enjoys being around him, it’s because of his money. This song is a melancholy acknowledgement of that.

songs.title: Neptune

description.plain:
“Neptune” is a collaboration between XO members NAV, Belly and 88GLAM. The full song leaked on May 19, 2018, after appearing on now-deleted online tracklists for NAV’s 2018 album, Reckless, however, it didn’t make the final cut for the project.

The instrumental was later used officially for the song “FRIENDS,” which is the 6th track on JAY-Z’s and Beyoncé’s collab album EVERYTHING IS LOVE.

songs.title: My Space

description.plain:
“My Space” can be denoted as the sequel to NAV & Metro Boomin’s platinum-selling July 2017 single, “Call Me.”

Beginning the same way “Call Me“ ends – with a dial tone – this track contradicts his feelings from the 2017 track. Within “Call Me,“ NAV’s chorus begs for a partner:

Do you know how it feel to feel alone?
Bought myself a house, still feel like I ain’t home

On the contrary, within this track’s chorus, he realizes the mistake he made:

You don’t understand, I said I need my space (Woah)
Why you all up in my face? (Woah)

Realizing he has no time for groupie girls who only want him for his wealth and fame, NAV raps about the need for space from the fast paced life he leads.

songs.title: Bag

description.plain:
“Bag” is an unreleased track by NAV, first previewed in 2016 by Wheezy; since then, NAV has repeatedly teased releasing it. In an interview with Tim Westwood in August 2019, NAV responded to fan comments about releasing the song, saying he may drop it on Audiomack as a loosie for the fans.

The track leaked online on March 16, 2020. It’s unknown if the leak will have an effect on its potential release. The leaked version was dated 2017, so it’s possible that this is an early version.

songs.full_title: Do Ya Deed by NAV (Ft. SahBabii)
songs.title: Do Ya Deed

description.plain:
On “Do Ya Deed,” NAV recruits Atlanta artist SahBabii, marking the duo’s first collaboration.

In July 2020, NAV promoted Sah’s recently released album Barnacles on his Instagram story. Photos later emerged from a studio session between the two artists, further fueling anticipation for a collab.

Sah employs his signature effortless flow paired with his trademark witty lyricism, while NAV raps in his typical lackadaisical, auto-tuned delivery. The song’s chopped and screwed outro is reminiscent of NAV’s early songs such as “Myself,” “The Man,” and “On My Own.”

songs.title: Capping

description.plain:
“Capping” is an unreleased track by NAV. In typical fashion for NAV, it finds him speaking on the general topics of drug use, making money and being promiscuous.

NAV previewed an alternate version on his Snapchat on June 17, 2018, featuring a few different lyrics in the chorus. One such lyric which was removed that drew attention was:

“Don’t diss the brown boy, watch who you callin' a Paki”

It’s unknown why these lines were altered on the version that leaked online on June 13, 2019, though it could’ve been deemed offensive.

songs.title: Amazing

description.plain:
“Amazing” is an Auto-Tune-heavy track taken from the deluxe edition of NAV’s sophomore studio album Bad Habits, and features first time collaborator Future with production handled by Tay Keith.

NAV first teased the collaboration on a twitch stream with Ninja. Two days later he posted a photo on instagram with the release day.

The track finds them flexing their oppulence and extravagant lifestyle with subtle drug references.

songs.title: Pine Soul

description.plain:
On “Pine Soul,“ NAV references Pine-Sol, a brand of household cleaning products.

Notably, when opening the Pine-Sol website, this message is displayed:

Pine-Sol and other disinfectants are not suitable for consumption or injection under any circumstances.

He drops this reference to simply show he uses illegal drugs on the regular, whilst also rapping on his expensive cars and diamonds to boast about his fame and wealth.

NAV’s manager, Cash, originally leaked this track under the name “PineSol“ on April 21, 2020, in a now-deleted Audiomack release which can be heard here.

songs.title: Ball in Peace (Outro)

description.plain:
“Ball in Peace” is dedicated to NAV’s late friend, DJ and producer jayxxclusive3 who died on February 6, 2022, after escaping his automobile while being pulled over by police and falling over roofs till he died.

Since February 2022, a few excerpts of the song have been circulating. Through an Instagram post, NAV confirmed that the song would feature on Demons Protected by Angels and that he produced it on July 30, 2022.

songs.title: Wrong Decisions

description.plain:
“Wrong Decisions” is the second single from NAV’s fourth studio album, Demons Protected by Angels, and serves as his first solo release in nearly two years, following the release of his November 2020 mixtape, Emergency Tsunami. The self-produced song finds the Canadian rapper discussing the things that fame might cause him to worry about and make the wrong decisions.

NAV announced the release of the song the day before its release, sharing its title, cover art, and release date and announcing that he had solely produced the song on August 22, 2022. However, he had previewed the instrumental through an Instagram story in January or February of 2022, as he confirmed on his official Discord server.

The official music video for “Wrong Decisions” was released on August 24, 2022. It was supposed to be released the previous day alongside the release of the single, but was pushed back to the next day after that due to technical difficulties.

songs.title: Pickney

description.plain:
“Pickney” is a braggadocious song in which NAV boasts about his copious and hedonistic lifestyle over a Wheezy-produced instrumental. He raps about his cars, money, and women, also dropping references to multiple rappers and singers.

This song was fully played on the tenth episode of .WAV Radio, a radio show that is hosted by NAV’s close friend and frequent collaborator Travis Scott and Travis' DJ and fellow labelmate CHASE B. It then found a home on the bonus version of Emergency Tsunami, as the first of two bonus tracks, on November 11, 2020.

songs.title: Stella McCartney

description.plain:
“Stella McCartney” was released on the bonus version of NAV’s Emergency Tsunami, produced by Outtatown and Wheezy. The tune consists of Future and NAV rapping about their various designer purchases, from companies such as Stella McCartney, Goyard, Chrome Hearts, and Chanel, all over light and twinkly beat from Outtatown and Wheezy.

Future and NAV have numerous other collaborations, such as “My Business” or “Amazing.”

songs.title: Still Want You

description.plain:
“Still Want You” is an unreleased song by NAV. The song appears to use The Weeknd’s unreleased “Patient” as a reference track.

In the song, NAV mainly sings about how he wants someone and how he has feelings for her, but at the same time, he doesn’t want to show it. It leaked online on December 26, 2018.

songs.title: Beside Me

description.plain:
“Beside Me” (better known as “B-Side”) is a highly anticipated and unreleased single by NAV.

In this song, NAV talks about hanging with a girl and explaining how he can sort of trust her, but at the same time doubts that thought in his head.

The song was first teased in mid-2018 by Music Mafia after they leaked a snippet of the song under the name “B-Side”. It leaked online later that year on December 9.

songs.title: Contradiction

description.plain:
“Contradiction” is an unreleased throwaway by NAV. It was recorded sometime in the first half of 2019. The track finds him speaking on the general topics of making money, drug usage and being promiscuous. It leaked online on June 14, 2019.

Southside previewed an early version of the instrumental on Instagram live in January 2019. He later commented on the track under a fan-page’s Instagram post:

Dam who ever remade da beat robbed me never even heard the song

songs.title: Calling Everybody

description.plain:
“Calling Everbody” is an unreleased track by NAV. In typical fashion for NAV, it finds him speaking on the general topics of drug use, making money and being promiscuous.

It was previewed multiple times by NAV via Snapchat in 2015. In early 2017, one of these snippets resurfaced, leading fans to repeatedly ask NAV to release it. NAV later stated that he lost the file, hence why it could never be finished and released. Despite this, the song later leaked on May 9, 2019.

The cover art was made by Shariff, who also created the art for NAV’s self-titled debut mixtape. Shariff posted the cover art in a since-deleted Instagram post in January 2017. Since the song was never released, the cover art was also discarded.

songs.title: Rari

description.plain: Previewed by Wheezy Beats on Snapchat in early 2017.  Made during the same studio session as “Bag”. The song was compiled with the snippet for “Bag” and was thus presumed to be the same song. However, in November 2019, Rex Kudo confirmed this to be a separate song. Cash XO leaked it on audiomack on May 10, 2020. Actual name of the track is “Now Its Over”. The track is also thought to have a second verse due to the fact that part of the original snippet is missing.

description.plain: “Fast Life” is an unreleased throwaway by NAV that finds him questioning loyalties while flexing his new-found wealth and success. The track is thought to have been recorded sometime in late 2016 to early 2017; it appeared on an early tracklist for NAV’s self-titled project. The song didn’t see a release, however, and later leaked online on December 23, 2018.

description.plain:
“I’m The Man,” sometimes known as “Playboy” or “The Man Pt. 2,” is an unreleased throwaway by NAV. Its actual title is unknown. The track finds NAV speaking on the general topics of making money, drug use and designer clothes.

The song was previewed back in 2017 by NAV, with fans seeing it as a sequel of sorts to his 2016 release, “The Man,” hence the unofficial title of “The Man Pt. 2.” Another snippet surfaced in late 2018, with the full song later leaking on June 13, 2019.

songs.title: Manage

description.plain:
“Manage” is an unreleased track by NAV. In typical fashion for NAV, it finds him speaking on the general topics of drug use, making money and being promiscuous. It leaked online on May 27, 2019.

The song was previewed via Snapchat in 2015, however, it was never finished and released; the song is quite short, featuring only one verse and chorus with a lot of trailing instrumental.

songs.title_with_featured: She Want More (beibs in the trap Demo)

description.plain:
“beibs in the trap” is a collaboration between Travis Scott and NAV that appears on Travis' 2016 sophomore effort, Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight. This is NAV’s original demo titled “She Want More”.

In 2015, NAV teased the existence of the song via a now-deleted tweet of some of the lyrics. It appears, then, that NAV gave the song to Travis and they reworked it for his album. Some notable differences in the demo can be found solely in his verse: it appears to use an earlier vocal take and has a few minor lyric differences.

songs.title: Casket

description.plain:
“Casket” is the name given to an unreleased collaboration between NAV, Preme and SAIF.

Details about the song are largely unknown, however, the original file is dated August 31, 2018. It’s unfinished, featuring a large portion of instrumental in place of vocals. There are rumours of a second NAV verse, however, it remains unheard.

The song entered circulation heavily in late 2018 after SAIF gave the song to a friend and it spread. It leaked online on January 4, 2019.

songs.title: Breaking News Intro

description.plain: “Breaking News Intro” is the opening track for Emergency Tsunami. It is a spoken dialogue by American lawyer and politician Conor Lamb, who also speaks again on the mixtape’s ending track of the same name. This introduction also uses the instrumental of “Friends & Family,” the track on the project that succeeds this.

It was a beautiful spring day, it was sunny outside. Uh, I had just come home from a, uh, little errand to the grocery store, and all of a sudden, bam, it just hit, and you—you could tell this was really different—instantly—from the other little tremors that we've had before. I mean, it just picked up with intensity. It ramped up. A gentle little shaking and things started coming off the shelves. Things started falling off our desks and you could hear this strange, eerie, creaking sound of all the buildings all around us, as they werе kind of shaken by this, uh, by the tremor of thе ground. (A tsunami warning has been issued.)Embed

songs.title: Paranoid

description.plain: “Paranoid” is an unreleased throwaway by NAV that finds him reflecting on the problems brought about by his new-found fame. The track was likely uploaded to NAV’s original SoundCloud in 2014, however, unlike other deleted tracks such as “Diamonds”, it wasn’t recovered. It later resurfaced on August 30, 2019.

songs.title: Gone

description.plain:
“Gone,” sometimes referred to as “Company,” is an unreleased throwaway by NAV, thought to have been recorded during sessions for his 2018 debut album, RECKLESS. It finds NAV struggling with the dilemma of wanting a girl by his side, but knowing he won’t be faithful.

A snippet of the track surfaced in June 2019, with a very short version of the track leaking online on November 30, 2019. The full version of the track later leaked on December 12, 2019.

songs.title: Addict

description.plain:
The remake of “Addict”, “Habits,” found a release on the deluxe version of NAV’s 2019 release, Bad Habits. This is the first version of the track, originally seen on an early tracklist for the anticipated collaborative album between NAV and Rex Kudo.

The track was recorded on February 6, 2017 and previewed on February 11, 2017. The snippet became a fan-favorite, with many requests for NAV to release it. This track features an alternate verse and a tweaked instrumental compared to the remake, “Habits.” It’s unknown if it will ever see the light of day.

songs.title: The Day*

description.plain: “The Day” was previewed by NAV in late 2015. He was asked about the song in an interview with Tim Westwood but only discussed the fate of another highly anticipated snippet, Bag, which finally found a release on the deluxe version of NAV’s 2020 release, Good Intentions. This snippet, however, has not even been acknowledged by NAV at all.

songs.title: Fell in Love (Demo)

description.plain:
“Fell in Love” is an early NAV track that was released as a single via SoundCloud and YouTube in early 2016. This is the demo of the song that leaked online on November 13, 2019.

It was previewed by NAV in early 2016, prior to joining XO Records. Compared to the final release, this version of the track is incomplete and features an entirely different instrumental. He references OVO in the line “Owls inside my shoes and Owls on my shirt” in this version, implying he was contemplating on signing to OVO at the time, whereas the released version references OVO and XO both in the line “Owls inside my shoes and XO my shirt”.
